\h Heroes and Guides
\toc1 Various Heroes and Guides
\toc2 Heroes and Guides
\toc3 Ldrs
\mt2 The accounts of
\mt1 Various Heroes and Guides
\mt3 commonly called вҖҳJudgesвҖҷ
\is1 Introduction
\ip This document commonly called вҖҳ\bk Judges\bk*вҖҷ, contains a collection of accounts of вҖҳ\bk Various Heroes and Guides/Leaders\bk*вҖҷ who helped to rescue the Israeli people from their oppressors. It covers the times from their invasion of Canaan through to just before their first king. Most of these heroes or guides were actually warriors. Shimshon (commonly called вҖҳSamsonвҖҷ) is the best-known of all of them, and his story can be read in chapters 13вҖ“16.
\ip From this document we can learn that Yisrael (вҖҳIsraelвҖҷ in older English translations) prospered when they obeyed Yahweh's instructions, but when they disobeyed, then God allowed other peoples and nations to oppress them. However, God is always ready and prepared to save his people whenever they turn away from their disobedience and return again to obeying the instructions that he'd given them.
\ip The previous book was named after the main character Yehoshua (Joshua) and the following books (Ruth and 1 Shemuel/Samuel) are named after their main characters, but this document with somewhere around a dozen important characters, has no single prominent character that it could be named after. Instead it's traditionally named вҖҳJudgesвҖҷ in English because of around twenty uses of the Hebrew root вҖҳЧ©ЧҒЦёЧӨЦ·ЧҳвҖҷ (shafat) often in roots normally translated as вҖҳjudgedвҖҷ. Despite that, there's not a single account in this document of these leaders judging the cases and conflicts of the common people. This dilemma offers two possible interpretations: 1/ that these leaders (often military leaders) did judge cases for the common people, but those details aren't recorded, or 2/ (which we've leaned more towards) that this Hebrew word has a wider range of meaning, and so we've leaned towards the English word вҖҳguidedвҖҷ or вҖҳledвҖҷ in these contexts.
\iot Main components of this account
\io1 The events up until Yehoshua's death \ior 1:1вҖ“2:10\ior*
\io1 The various heroes/guides of Yisrael \ior 2:11вҖ“16:31\ior*
\io1 Various other events \ior 17:1вҖ“21:25\ior*
\rem This is still a very early look into the unfinished text of the Open English Translation of the Bible. Please double-check the text in advance before using in public.
\ie
\c 1
\s1 Yehudah and Simeon capture Adoni-Bezek
\rem /s1 Completing the conquest of Canaan; Israel Fights the Remaining Canaanites; Israel's Failure to Complete the Conquest of Canaan; Judah and Simeon Conquer the Land; The Tribes of Judah and Simeon Capture Adonibezek
\p
\v 1 After Yehoshua's deathВҰ111579, the IsraelisВҰ111583 asked YahwehВҰ111584, вҖң\add вүҲWhich tribe should goВҰ111587 firstВҰ111593 to attack the CanaanitesВҰ111592\add*?вҖқ
\v 2 вҖңYehudahВҰ111599 will goВҰ111600 first,вҖқ YahwehВҰ111598 \add вүҲanswered\add*. вҖңListen, I'veВҰ111602 \add вүҲalready determined that they'll conquer\add* the land.вҖқ
\p
\v 3 Then the YehudahВҰ111609 \add leaders\add* saidВҰ111608 to \add the tribe of\add* SimeonВҰ111610, вҖң\add вүҲCome\add* withВҰ111614 \add #us\add* into the region that we've been allocated andВҰ111608 we can fightВҰ111615 together againstВҰ111616 the CanaanitesВҰ111616. Then we'll do the same inВҰ111614 yourВҰ111622 area.вҖқ SoВҰ111608 \add вүҲthe warriors from the two tribes worked together\add*.
\v 4 WhenВҰ111628 \add *they\add* attacked, YahwehВҰ111630 \add вүҲgaveВҰ111629 them victory over\add* the CanaanitesВҰ111633 and the PerizzitesВҰ111634 and they killed tenВҰ111638 thousandВҰ111639 men atВҰ111635 BezekВҰ111637.
\v 5 They \add вүҲconfronted\add* AdoniВҰ111645-Bezek inВҰ111647 Bezek and foughtВҰ111648 against him (thenВҰ111642 eventually defeatingВҰ111650 the CanaanitesВҰ111653 and the PerizzitesВҰ111656).
\v 6 AdoniВҰ111659-BezekВҰ111660 \add tried to\add* flee butВҰ111658 they chased him and captured him, cutting off his thumbsВҰ111668 and bigВҰ111670 toes.
\v 7 вҖңSeventy kingsВҰ111678 had their thumbsВҰ111679 and bigВҰ111681 toes chopped off,вҖқ AdoniВҰ111673-BezekВҰ111675 saidВҰ111672, вҖңand were gatheringВҰ111684 scraps of food beneath my tableВҰ111686. Just as I have done, so GodВҰ111693 has repaidВҰ111690 to me.вҖқ ThenВҰ111672 they took him to YerushalemВҰ111695 and he diedВҰ111696 thereВҰ111697.
\s1 The capture of Yerushalem and Hebron
\rem /s1 The Tribe of Judah Conquers Jerusalem and Hebron
\p
\v 8 The warriors from YehudahВҰ111703 attacked YerushalemВҰ111704 and capturedВҰ111705 the city, killing the inhabitants and setting the city onВҰ111704 fire.
\v 9 ThenВҰ111717 theyВҰ111718 fought againstВҰ111722 the CanaanitesВҰ111722 who lived in the hill countryВҰ111724, in the southern \add wilderness\add*, andВҰ111717 in the \add western\add* foothills.
\v 10 \add *They\add* also fought the CanaanitesВҰ111732 inВҰ111734 KiriathВҰ111740-Arba (now known as HebronВҰ111734) and killed SheshaiВҰ111744, AhimanВҰ111747, and TalmaiВҰ111750.
\s1 Otniel captures Debir
\rem /s1 Othniel Conquers the City of Debir
\r (Josh. 15:13-19)
\p
\v 11 From thereВҰ111753 \add #they\add* \add вүҲfought againstВҰ111754\add* KiriathВҰ111764-SepherВҰ111764 (now known as DebirВҰ111757).
\v 12 CalebВҰ111767 \add had\add* saidВҰ111766, вҖңWhoever attacksВҰ111770 KiriathВҰ111773-SepherВҰ111775 andВҰ111766 capturesВҰ111776 it \add вүҲcan marry\add* my daughterВҰ111782 Aksah.вҖқ
\v 13 OtnielВҰ111786 (son of Caleb'sВҰ111791 younger brotherВҰ111790 KenazВҰ111789) capturedВҰ111785 it so \add @Caleb\add* gaveВҰ111794 his daughterВҰ111800 AksahВҰ111799 to him to become his wife.
\v 14 \add вүҲAfter the wedding\add*, she urgedВҰ111805 \add @Otniel\add* to askВҰ111806 her fatherВҰ111809 for a fieldВҰ111810. WhenВҰ111803 she got off her donkeyВҰ111813, CalebВҰ111817 asked her, вҖңWhat can I do for you?вҖқ
\v 15 вҖңGive me a blessingВҰ111827,вҖқ she \add вүҲrequested\add*. вҖңAlthough you'veВҰ111831 givenВҰ111831 me land in the southern wilderness, giveВҰ111832 me some springs of waterВҰ111835 as well.вҖқ SoВҰ111822 CalebВҰ111839 gaveВҰ111836 her the upperВҰ111842 springs andВҰ111822 the lowerВҰ111845 springs.
\s1 The victory of descendants of Yehudah and Benyamin
\rem /s1 The Victories of the Tribes of Judah and Benjamin
\p
\v 16 The KenitesВҰ111849 (descendants of Mosheh'sВҰ111851 father-in-law), left the cityВҰ111853 of palmВҰ111854 treesВҰ111854 \add (Yericho)\add* and went with Yehudah'sВҰ111858 descendants to the southern wildernessВҰ111859 near AradВҰ111863 and lived with the peopleВҰ111868 \add there\add*.
\v 17 ThenВҰ111870 the warriors of YehudahВҰ111871 and SimeonВҰ111874 conquered the CanaanitesВҰ111879 livingВҰ111880 at Tsefat and destroyed \add @the cityВҰ111889\add*. \add Now\add* it's calledВҰ111884 HormahВҰ111890 \add (which means вҖҳcomplete destructionвҖҷ)\add*.
\v 18 \add *They\add* also capturedВҰ111892 GazaВҰ111896, AshkelonВҰ111902, and EkronВҰ111908 and \add all\add* their surrounding territories.
\rem /s1 Israel Fails to Conquer the Land
\v 19 YahwehВҰ111914 helped YehudahВҰ111917 andВҰ111921 \add #they\add* tookВҰ111921 possessionВҰ111921 of the hill countryВҰ111924, although they weren't able to conquer the people living down in the plainsВҰ111931 because they had iron on their chariotsВҰ111934.
\v 20 They gaveВҰ111938 HebronВҰ111942 to CalebВҰ111939 just as MoshehВҰ111945 had directed, andВҰ111938 he dispossessedВҰ111946 the threeВҰ111950 sonsВҰ111951 of the AnakВҰ111952 from thereВҰ111947.\x + \xo 1:20: \xt Josh 15:13-14.\x*
\v 21 \add вүҲHowever\add* Benyamin'sВҰ111962 descendants didn'tВҰ111959 drive the YebusitesВҰ111956 livingВҰ111957 in Yerushalem out, so \add *they\add* have lived among the Benyamites in Yerushalem to this dayВҰ111971.\x + \xo 1:21: \xt Josh 15:63; 2Sam 5:6; 1Ch 11:4.\x*
\s1 Efrayim and Menashsheh conquer Beyt-El
\rem /s1 The Tribes of Ephraim and Manasseh Conquer Beyt-El
\p
\v 22 AlsoВҰ111982 Yosef'sВҰ111978 descendants attacked Beyt-El, and YahwehВҰ111985 \add вүҲhelped\add* them.
\v 23 \add *They\add* sent spies out to Beyt-ElВҰ111991 (previously called LuzВҰ111999)
\v 24 and \add *they\add* saw a man comingВҰ112004 out of the city and told him, вҖңPleaseВҰ112012 show us an entranceВҰ112014 into the city, and we'll be kind to you.вҖқ
\v 25 \add вүҲSoВҰ112020\add* he showedВҰ112020 them an entranceВҰ112023, and \add @their warriors\add* \add attacked and\add* \add вүҲkilled the inhabitants\add*, butВҰ112020 they let the manВҰ112034 and his familyВҰ112039 goВҰ112040 free.
\v 26 The manВҰ112043 wentВҰ112042 to the land of the HittitesВҰ112045 and \add вүҲfounded\add* a cityВҰ112047 and called it LuzВҰ112050 (which it's still called to this dayВҰ112054).
\s1 The locals not driven out by the Israelis
\rem /s1 People Who Were Not Driven Out by the Israelites
\p
\v 27 \add вүҲHowever\add* Menashsheh'sВҰ112061 \add descendants\add* didn'tВҰ112058 drive out those living in Beyt-Shan, Taanak, DorВҰ112080, Yibleam, or Meggidon, because the CanaanitesВҰ112099 were determinedВҰ112098 \add вүҲto keep living there\add*.\x + \xo 1:27-28: \xt Josh 17:11-13.\x*
\v 28 (\add Later,\add* the Israelis becameВҰ112107 strongerВҰ112107 andВҰ112104 \add вүҲthey forcedВҰ112113 the CanaanitesВҰ112112 to work for them as their slaves\add*, butВҰ112104 they didn'tВҰ112115 driveВҰ112114 them out.)
\v 29 Nor did Efrayim'sВҰ112119 \add descendants\add* drive the CanaanitesВҰ112124 out of GezerВҰ112126, so \add *they\add* continued to live among them.\x + \xo 1:29: \xt Josh 16:10.\x*
\p
\v 30 Zebulun'sВҰ112133 \add descendants\add* didn'tВҰ112134 drive the CanaanitesВҰ112145 out of KitronВҰ112139 or NahalolВҰ112143, so theyВҰ112147 continued to live among them and were \add вүҲforcedВҰ112148 to work as slaves\add*.
\p
\v 31 Asher'sВҰ112151 \add descendants\add* didn'tВҰ112152 drive out those who were living in Akko, Tsidon, AhlabВҰ112164, AczibВҰ112167, HelbahВҰ112170, AfekВҰ112173, or RehobВҰ112176,
\v 32 \add вүҲSoВҰ112178\add* the AsheritesВҰ112179 lived withВҰ112180 the CanaanitesВҰ112181 who \add still\add* lived inВҰ112180 the region because they didn'tВҰ112185 driveВҰ112186 them out.
\p
\v 33 Naftali'sВҰ112189 \add descendants\add* didn'tВҰ112190 drive out those who were living inВҰ112206 Beyt-ShemeshВҰ112198 or Beyt-AnatВҰ112204, so theyВҰ112216 continued to live among them and were \add вүҲforcedВҰ112218 to work as slaves\add*.
\p
\v 34 The AmoritesВҰ112222 forced Dan'sВҰ112227 descendantsВҰ112225 to live in the hill countryВҰ112228, because theyВҰ112221 didn'tВҰ112231 allowВҰ112232 them to comeВҰ112233 down to the plainsВҰ112234.
\v 35 The Amorites were determinedВҰ112236 to liveВҰ112238 atВҰ112239 MtВҰ112239. HeresВҰ112241, inВҰ112239 Ayyalon andВҰ112236 ShaalbimВҰ112243 (butВҰ112236 when Yosef'sВҰ112248 descendants became stronger, theyВҰ112249 forcedВҰ112250 the Amorites \add вүҲto work as slaves\add*).
\v 36 The AmoritesВҰ112253 borderВҰ112252 went from the Scorpion Pass through SelaВҰ112256 andВҰ112257 upwardВҰ112257 from there.
\c 2
\s1 God's messenger comes to Bokim
\rem /s1 The Angel of the Lord at Bochim; Result of disobedience; Israel's Disobedience; The Angel of the Lord at Bokim; The Lord's Messenger Comes to Bokim
\p
\v 1 Then Yahweh's messengerВҰ112261 went from GilgalВҰ112266 to BokimВҰ112269 and told \add the Israelis\add*, вҖңI broughtВҰ112272 you all out of EgyptВҰ112274 and led you here to this land that I promised to your ancestorsВҰ112282. I had said that I wouldn't ever breakВҰ112286 my agreement with you all,
\v 2 butВҰ112291 that you mustn't form treaties withВҰ112304 the peoples who lived here, rather you mustВҰ112300 tear down theirВҰ112299 altarsВҰ112299. ButВҰ112291 you all haven't obeyed what I said. What have you \add gone andВҰ112291\add* done?\x + \xo 2:2: \xt Exo 34:12-13; Deu 7:2-5.\x*
\v 3 \add вүҲSoВҰ112310\add* I'm telling you that I won'tВҰ112312 driveВҰ112314 your enemies out ahead of you, \add вүҲbutВҰ112310\add* they'll be like thorns in your sidesВҰ112319 andВҰ112310 you'll all end up being enslaved to theirВҰ112320 \add вүҲidols\add*.вҖқ
\v 4 WhenВҰ112325 Yahweh's messengerВҰ112327 finished saying that, the people wept loudly,
\v 5 so they calledВҰ112346 that placeВҰ112349 BokimВҰ112351 \add (which means вҖҳweepingвҖҷ)\add* andВҰ112352 they \add вүҲoffered sacrificesВҰ112352\add* to YahwehВҰ112355 thereВҰ112354.
\s1 The death of Yehoshua
\rem /s1 Death of Joshua; Disobedience and Defeat; The Death of Joshua
\p
\v 6 Then Yehoshua dismissedВҰ112358 the people and the \add вүҲtribes went to their various regions\add* to take possessionВҰ112369 of the land.
\v 7 The peopleВҰ112375 \add вүҲobeyed\add* Yahweh \add вүҲas longВҰ112387 as Yehoshua andВҰ112382 the eldersВҰ112385 who had seenВҰ112392 the greatВҰ112398 things thatВҰ112399 Yahweh had done for YisraelВҰ112401, were alive\add*.
\v 8 ThenВҰ112403 Yahweh's servantВҰ112408 Yehoshua (son of NunВҰ112407) diedВҰ112403 at the age of 110
\v 9 andВҰ112416 they buriedВҰ112416 himВҰ112417 inВҰ112418 his allocated land atВҰ112418 TimnatВҰ112420-Heres, inside Efrayim'sВҰ112424 hillВҰ112426 countryВҰ112423 territoryВҰ112418 northВҰ112425 of MtВҰ112426. GaashВҰ112428.\x + \xo 2:9: \xt Josh 19:49-50.\x*
\s1 Yisrael (Israel) turns from Yahweh
\rem /s1 Israel Disobeys the Lord
\p
\v 10 WhenВҰ112430 all of thatВҰ112443 generation \add вүҲhad passed away\add*, the next generation didn'tВҰ112444 know YahwehВҰ112449 or \add even\add* know about what he'd done for \add вүҲthe IsraelisВҰ112456\add*.
\rem /s1 Israel's Unfaithfulness; Israel Stops Worshipping the Lord
\v 11 \add *They\add* did \add вүҲthings that YahwehВҰ112467 considered evilВҰ112465\add* and worshipped BaalВҰ112471 \add idols\add*
\v 12 and abandonedВҰ112473 the god of theirВҰ112479 ancestorsВҰ112479, Yahweh, the one who broughtВҰ112480 them out of EgyptВҰ112483. \add Instead\add* they went afterВҰ112485 otherВҰ112488 godsвҖ”the gods of the peopleВҰ112490 aroundВҰ112492 them. They worshipped them and thatВҰ112491 made Yahweh angry.
\v 13 They abandonedВҰ112502 YahwehВҰ112505 and \add вүҲworshipped\add* the BaalВҰ112507 and AshtarotВҰ112508 \add idols\add*.
\v 14 \add вүҲSoВҰ112510\add* YahwehВҰ112513 \add вүҲgot angry withВҰ112514\add* YisraelВҰ112514 so \add вүҲhe caused raiders to come and take their property\add* and \add вүҲhe allowed their enemies to become more powerful\add* so they could no longer standВҰ112529 against them.
\v 15 \add вүҲWhenever the Israelis wentВҰ112536 into battle\add*, YahwehВҰ112539 \add вүҲworked against them\add* just like \add *he'd\add* said he would and they became very distressedВҰ112551.
\rem /s1 The Lord Rescues His People; The first judges
\p
\v 16 ThenВҰ112555 YahwehВҰ112556 \add вүҲgave them\add* leaders\f + \fr 2:16 \ft Traditionally called вҖҳjudgesвҖҷ in most English translations, but that modern term doesn't fit their various functions in this account at all well. (вҖҳLeadersвҖҷ isn't perfect either but it's generic enough to cover most of their roles.)\f* to save them from the raiders.
\v 17 \add вүҲHowever\add* they wouldn't listenВҰ112567 to \add those\add* leaders \add either\add*вҖ”continuing to prostituteВҰ112569 themselves to otherВҰ112572 godsВҰ112571 and bowing down to idols. They rapidly turnedВҰ112575 away from their ancestors' ways and \add вүҲshowed no interest\add* in obeying Yahweh's instructions.
\v 18 Whenever YahwehВҰ112595 \add вүҲgave them\add* a leader, he would \add вүҲsupport\add* that leader and would save them from theirВҰ112617 enemiesВҰ112606 during that leader's life, becauseВҰ112592 he pitied \add @the people\add* when they groanedВҰ112614 \add вүҲfrom being tormented and oppressedВҰ112616\add*.
\v 19 \add вүҲButВҰ112619 thenВҰ112619 atВҰ112621 the death of that leader\add*, they would turn back and behave more corruptlyВҰ112624 than their ancestorsВҰ112625вҖ”following otherВҰ112629 godsВҰ112628 and bowingВҰ112631 down to \add @idols\add*. They didn'tВҰ112633 stop any of their evil activities or their shameless behaviour
\v 20 \add вүҲso\add* YahwehВҰ112642 \add вүҲwas very angry\add* atВҰ112643 YisraelВҰ112643 and saidВҰ112644, вҖңThis nationВҰ112648 has broken the agreement thatВҰ112653 I made withВҰ112643 theirВҰ112657 ancestorsВҰ112657 and haven't \add вүҲdone what I toldВҰ112654 them to\add*.
\v 21 I won'tВҰ112665 keep driving the people groups away thatВҰ112673 \add remained\add* when Yehoshua diedВҰ112677,
\v 22 so as to use them to test YisraelВҰ112684 \add to see\add* whetherВҰ112685 \add @the IsraelisВҰ112690\add* will obey my instructions like theirВҰ112695 ancestorsВҰ112695 did, or not.
\v 23 \add вүҲSoВҰ112700\add* YahwehВҰ112701 allowed those people groups to stay onВҰ112711, andВҰ112700 hence they hadn't been \add вүҲhanded over\add* to YehoshuaВҰ112713.
\c 3
\s1 The remaining kingdoms in Canaan
\rem /s1 Nations Remaining in the Land; The Nations Left in Canaan; The Nations Remaining in the Land
\p
\v 1 The \add following\add* are the kingdomsВҰ112717 whichВҰ112718 YahwehВҰ112720 allowed to remain so as to test the \add newer generations\add* of YisraelВҰ112725 who hadn't experienced the battles inВҰ112722 CanaanВҰ112737
\v 2 (\add if\add* only for the sake of teachingВҰ112746 warfare to those generationsВҰ112742 who hadn't experiencedВҰ112753 itВҰ112753):
\v 3 the fiveВҰ112755 Philistine rulersВҰ112757 and the CanaanitesВҰ112761, the SidoniansВҰ112762, the HivitesВҰ112763 that live on Mt. LebanonВҰ112766 between Mt. BaalВҰ112769-Hermon and LeboВҰ112771-Hamat.\f + \fr 3:3 \ft Or, вҖҳthe entrance to HamatвҖҷ.\f*
\v 4 They were \add left\add* to test YisraelВҰ112779 to find out if they would obeyВҰ112781 Yahweh's instructionsВҰ112788 thatВҰ112786 had been given through MoshehВҰ112794 to theirВҰ112791 ancestorsВҰ112791,
\v 5 and \add so\add* the IsraelisВҰ112797 lived among the CanaanitesВҰ112800, the HittitesВҰ112801, the AmoritesВҰ112802, the PerizzitesВҰ112803, the HivitesВҰ112804, and the YebusitesВҰ112805.
\v 6 They took their daughters as wivesВҰ112812, and gave their own daughters \add to be married\add* to their sons, and they \add вүҲworshipped\add* their gods.
\s1 Otniel
\rem /s1 Othniel; Othniel Becomes Israel's Judge
\p
\v 7 \add вүҲSo\add* the \add вүҲIsraelisВҰ112827 did things considered evilВҰ112830 by\add* Yahweh and theyВҰ112824 forgotВҰ112833 about theirВҰ112837 godВҰ112837 Yahweh, \add вүҲinstead\add* serving the BaalВҰ112841 and Asherot \add idols\add*.
\v 8 \add Because of that,\add* YahwehВҰ112849 \add вүҲwas very angry\add* withВҰ112850 YisraelВҰ112850, so he \add вүҲhanded them over to\add* KingВҰ112855 CushanВҰ112864-Rishathaim of AramВҰ112857-Naharaim \add (Mesopotamia)\add*. The IsraelisВҰ112861 servedВҰ112858 him for eightВҰ112866 yearsВҰ112867
\v 9 \add вүҲbutВҰ112869 when\add* theyВҰ112869 criedВҰ112869 out to YahwehВҰ112875, \add *he\add* \add вүҲsent them\add* a \add вүҲleader to rescue\add* them: OtnielВҰ112883, son of Caleb'sВҰ112888 younger brotherВҰ112887 KenazВҰ112886.
\v 10 Yahweh's spiritВҰ112894 \add вүҲempowered\add* him and he led YisraelВҰ112900. He \add вүҲled them into battleВҰ112902\add* against KingВҰ112910 Cushan-Rishathaim of AramВҰ112911, and Yahweh \add вүҲhelped them\add* defeat \add *him\add*.
\v 11 \add вүҲSoВҰ112918\add* the region had peaceВҰ112918 for fortyВҰ112920 years, andВҰ112918 thenВҰ112918 OtnielВҰ112923 (Kenaz'sВҰ112926 son) diedВҰ112922.
\s1 Ehud
\rem /s1 Ehud; Ehud Becomes Israel's Judge
\p
\v 12 \add Once\add* again the IsraelisВҰ112931 started doingВҰ112932 things considered evil by YahwehВҰ112935, \add вүҲso\add* because of that, \add *he\add* strengthenedВҰ112936 KingВҰ112941 EglonВҰ112940 of MoabВҰ112943 against YisraelВҰ112931.
\v 13 \add @King Eglon\add* \add вүҲenlisted warriors from\add* the AmmonitesВҰ112962 and the AmalekitesВҰ112963, and theyВҰ112969 attacked YisraelВҰ112968 and captured \add Yericho,\add* the cityВҰ112972 of palmВҰ112973 treesВҰ112973,
\v 14 \add вүҲso\add* the IsraelisВҰ112978 servedВҰ112975 \add *him\add* for eighteenВҰ112985 years.
\p
\v 15 \add вүҲButВҰ112990\add* the Israelis criedВҰ112990 out to YahwehВҰ112996, \add *he\add* \add вүҲsent them\add* a \add вүҲleader to rescue\add* them: the left-hander EhudВҰ113003, son of GeraВҰ113006 the Benyamite. The Israelis sent him to carry the tributeВҰ113020 payment to KingВҰ113022 EglonВҰ113021 of MoabВҰ113023.
\v 16 \add вүҲNow\add* EhudВҰ113027 had made himself a double-edged swordВҰ113028вҖ”a short one about half a metre longвҖ”andВҰ113025 he strapped it to his rightВҰ113040 thighВҰ113039 beneath his clothesВҰ113037.
\v 17 ThenВҰ113042 he presentedВҰ113042 the tributeВҰ113045 to KingВҰ113049 EglonВҰ113046 of MoabВҰ113048, who was a very fat manВҰ113050,
\v 18 andВҰ113054 after leaving \add for home\add*, he sentВҰ113061 off the peopleВҰ113064 who'd \add actually\add* carriedВҰ113065 it \add all\add*.
\v 19 ThenВҰ113068 from the stone quarries \add that they'd reached\add* near GilgalВҰ113076, he returnedВҰ113069 andВҰ113068 told the king that he had a private messageВҰ113078 for him. The king told his attendantsВҰ113090 to be quiet thenВҰ113068 sent them out of the room.
